## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Also removed** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown; effectively dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, leave locks held, and cause torn writes. There is no workaround to re-enable it.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

            cts.Cancel();
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to preserve original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work supports cancellation (preferred)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfall: Cancellation ≠ Abort

The original `Thread.Abort()` **forcibly killed** the work. Neither replacement does that — `cts.Cancel()` is **cooperative**. The work must check the token:

```csharp
// ❌ Will NOT stop on timeout — ignores the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async (ct) => {
    Thread.Sleep(30_000);           // blocks, never checks ct
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ Correctly responds to cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async (ct) => {
    await Task.Delay(30_000, ct);   // throws on cancel
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**If you have truly uncooperative code** (e.g., a blocking third-party library), run it on a sacrificial thread you abandon (don't await) after timeout — but understand the thread keeps running until it finishes or the process exits. There is no safe way to forcibly terminate it in .NET 8.
